# =============================================================================
#  .live-gate — SAMPLE / SCHEMA REFERENCE  (copy to a workload repo's TOP LEVEL as `.live-gate`)
# =============================================================================
# A workload image repo ships this file at its repo root so the host pre-merge live-gate (Gate B)
# knows HOW to build + run + probe a candidate of THAT repo. It travels IN the PR head, so the gate
# always uses the contract that matches the code under test (no out-of-band host list to maintain).
#
# It is CONSUMED SAFELY — PARSED, NOT SOURCED. The host (live-gate-run.sh) reads this file line by
# line and assigns each KEY=VALUE with `printf -v`; it NEVER `.`/`source`s it, so nothing here is
# ever executed on the host (this file travels in the UNTRUSTED PR head). Grammar the parser enforces:
#   * one `KEY=VALUE` per line (no `;`-chained multi-assignment lines);
#   * keys must be schema keys (LIVE_GATE_TARGETS / CAND_* / the suffixed knobs below) — others ignored;
#   * single-quoted values are taken VERBATIM — `$( )`, backticks, `&&`, `;`, `<`, `>` inside them are
#     inert here and run only LATER, INSIDE the fenced container (single-quote your HEALTH/PROBE cmd);
#   * double-quoted values: only the bash escapes \" \$ \\ \` are unescaped, $VAR is NOT expanded, and
#     command substitution ($( ) or a backtick) is REFUSED (the whole contract is rejected RED);
#   * unquoted values must be a bare token (no spaces / shell metacharacters);
#   * no cross-variable references ($OTHER) — each key stands alone (inline the value).
# A contract that violates the grammar (or smuggles command substitution / chaining) is rejected with
# a RED verdict and is NOT executed.
#
# Resolution order the host applies (live-gate-run.sh):
#   1. this in-tree `.live-gate`            (preferred — auto-tracks the repo)
#   2. host ~/.config/live-gate/<repo>.env  (fallback preset, same schema)
#   3. generic default                       (single target: Containerfile, image HEALTHCHECK, no probe)
#
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
#  TARGETS
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# Space-separated list of build targets. EACH target is built + gated independently and ALL must be
# GREEN for the PR's overall verdict to be GREEN. Target names must match [A-Za-z0-9_].
# Omit LIVE_GATE_TARGETS entirely => a single implicit target named `default`.
#
#   LIVE_GATE_TARGETS="xrdp grd"
#
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
#  PER-TARGET KNOBS  — every key is suffixed with _<target> (e.g. CFILE_grd).
#  A bare/global form (CAND_FENCE, CAND_PROBE, HEALTH, CAND_CFILE, CAND_SECRET_*, CAND_MEMORY,
#  CAND_PIDS, CAND_HEALTH_*) acts as the fallback for any target that does not set its own — this
#  is also how a legacy single-set preset (no LIVE_GATE_TARGETS) is consumed.
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
#
#  CFILE_<t>   — the Containerfile to build for this target, relative to the repo root.
#                Default: Containerfile. THIS is how a multi-lineage repo points grd at its own
#                Containerfile.grd instead of the default xrdp Containerfile.
#                  CFILE_xrdp="Containerfile"
#                  CFILE_grd="Containerfile.grd"
#
#  FENCE_<t>   — the podman run flags for the disposable launch = the workload's REAL run.sh
#                contract MINUS the public publish (-p) and MINUS real secrets/volumes.
#                DEFAULT WHEN UNSET: the HARDEST fence `--network=none --cap-drop=ALL`. The probe
#                runs on the candidate's OWN loopback via `podman exec`, so a loopback-only workload
#                needs NO egress — leave the fence unset to stay networkless. A target that
#                genuinely needs egress / devices / systemd OPTS IN here EXPLICITLY, e.g. a
#                systemd-PID-1 lineage:
#                  FENCE_grd="--systemd=always --cgroupns=host -v /sys/fs/cgroup:/sys/fs/cgroup:rw --device /dev/fuse"
#                The gate ALWAYS adds its own --rm + a throwaway --name + hard --memory/--pids-limit.
#                NEVER put a publish flag here: the gate is loopback-only by construction and FAILS
#                CLOSED (RED) on any -p / --publish / -P / --publish-all in the resolved fence.
#
#  HEALTH_<t>  — explicit health-cmd (OCI build drops the Containerfile HEALTHCHECK, so the gate
#                passes one explicitly). Runs inside the candidate; exit 0 = healthy.
#                  HEALTH_xrdp='pgrep -x sshd'
#
#  PROBE_<t>   — the "does it actually serve" access-path assertion, run INSIDE the candidate via
#                `podman exec` (hits the candidate's OWN loopback — nothing is published to the
#                host). Exit 0 = serves. Stronger than HEALTH (a healthy-but-not-serving image
#                fails here). Omit for a health-only gate.
#                  PROBE_xrdp='[ "$(curl -sk -o /dev/null -w "%{http_code}" https://127.0.0.1:8443/)" = 200 ]'
#                PROBE may also INVOKE A SHIPPED SCRIPT for richer, lineage-aware assertions — e.g.
#                  PROBE_grd='bash /usr/local/share/<repo>/bin/gate-deep-probe.sh grd'
#                where the script is COPY'd into the image (no Containerfile change, no new packages).
#                It can prove far more than "serves": the desktop SESSION is actually RENDERING, the
#                RDP server is configured, the Guacamole auth chain is wired, multi-user per-user ports
#                are bound — all inside the loopback candidate, self-diagnosing (a failed check dumps
#                its reason into the RED verdict for in-loop iteration). Keep it loopback-only +
#                tool-frugal: a real RDP-pixel frame needs a PUBLISHED port + host-side
#                xfreerdp/Xvfb/ImageMagick, so that stays operator-run. Proven by fedora-desktop's
#                deeper Gate-B probe — zero host/apparatus change (the gate is workload-agnostic).
#
#  SECRET_MOUNT_<t> + SECRET_ENV_<t>
#              — scratch secrets for a target whose entrypoint requires a secrets file. SECRET_ENV
#                is KEY=VALUE lines (newline-separated); the gate writes them 0600 and bind-mounts
#                the file READ-ONLY at SECRET_MOUNT. Values are DISPOSABLE test values — NEVER real,
#                NEVER baked into a layer, NEVER logged. The gate never logs in; it only needs the
#                entrypoint's fail-fast required keys present so the candidate provisions + serves.
#                  SECRET_MOUNT_xrdp='/etc/myapp/secrets.env'
#                  SECRET_ENV_xrdp='ADMIN_PW=gate-scratch-not-a-real-secret'
#
#  MEMORY_<t> / PIDS_<t>          — gate-imposed resource caps (default 2g / 512). Raise for heavy
#                                   targets (full desktop + JVM/Tomcat + DB).
#  HEALTH_START_<t>               — --health-start-period (default 90s).
#  HEALTH_TRIES_<t> / HEALTH_SLEEP_<t> — gate's healthy-wait budget = TRIES × SLEEP s (default 18 × 6).
#
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
#  MINIMAL EXAMPLE — a single-target, loopback-only sshd box (networkless fence by default):
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
#   LIVE_GATE_TARGETS="default"
#   CFILE_default="Containerfile"
#   HEALTH_default='pgrep -x sshd'
#   PROBE_default="timeout 6 bash -c 'exec 3<>/dev/tcp/127.0.0.1/22; read -t 5 -u 3 b; case \"\$b\" in SSH-*) exit 0;; *) exit 1;; esac'"
#
# A full multi-lineage example (xrdp + grd, systemd fence, scratch secrets, raised caps) is the
# shipped host fallback live-gate-presets/fedora-desktop.env — read it as a worked reference.
